<TITLE> Zenit coach Advocaat tells Putin he may return home </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MOSCOW, Sept 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Zenit St Petersburg's Dutch coach Dick Advocaat told Russian Prime Minister Vladimir Putin on Saturday that he was thinking of returning home to spend more time with his family. Advocaat's contract with the UEFA Cup holders and domestic league champions runs out in November. "I have to take a serious decision because my close ones want me to go home," Advocaat was quoted by news agencies as telling Putin during a meeting held on the occasion of the Dutchman's 61st birthday. "Unfortunately, I am not young and I have to think about spending more time with my family." Advocaat took charge at Zenit, backed by Russia's biggest firm Gazprom, in 2006 after stepping down as South Korea manager when his team were eliminated from the World Cup finals in Germany. He previously led the Netherlands to the quarter-finals of the 1994 World Cup and the semi-finals of Euro 2004. Zenit, Putin's hometown team, became the first Russian team to lift the European Super Cup, beating Manchester United 2-1 last month. Their chances of retaining their domestic title have dwindled and they lie seventh in the 16-team league with nine matches to play
